You should be able to add multiple Theme Names for colour customisation. May be like this

```
workbench.colorCustomizations": {
 "[Night Owl No Italics, Night Owl]": {
   "activityBar.background": "#000C1D",
   "activityBar.border": "#102a44",
   "sideBar.background": "#001122",
   "sideBar.border": "#102a44",
   "sideBar.foreground": "#8BADC1"
  }
}
```

If you have to do that right now it's not supported you have to repeat the same for two different theme like this.

```
workbench.colorCustomizations": {
 "[Night Owl]": {
   "activityBar.background": "#000C1D",
   "activityBar.border": "#102a44",
   "sideBar.background": "#001122",
   "sideBar.border": "#102a44",
   "sideBar.foreground": "#8BADC1"
  },
 "[Night Owl No Italics]": {
   "activityBar.background": "#000C1D",
   "activityBar.border": "#102a44",
   "sideBar.background": "#001122",
   "sideBar.border": "#102a44",
   "sideBar.foreground": "#8BADC1"
  }
}
```

I rely on `onDidStartDebugSession` to track my debug sessions launching, and then use that information when handling custom events. In current insiders, it seems that the custom events can arrive before `onDidStartDebugSession` has even fired, which means I'm unable to handle them correctly.

I don't know for certain, but I would guess that the start event should always fire first?

```ts
context.subscriptions.push(vs.debug.onDidReceiveDebugSessionCustomEvent((e) => {
			logWarn('onDidReceiveDebugSessionCustomEvent!!!!!!');
});

context.subscriptions.push(vs.debug.onDidStartDebugSession(async (s) => {
			logWarn('onDidStartDebugSession!!!!!!');
});
```

![Screenshot 2019-04-03 at 10 53 40 am](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1078012/55470124-ebf0ed00-55fe-11e9-95dc-74e10a46024f.png)

@weinand @isidorn I don't know if this is at all related to the timing issue we saw in a previous version?
